00.Introduction¶

(a) Motivation¶

Ever since the Covid-19 crisis slashed the market by more than 30% back in March 2020, the U.S. stock market has risen for more than a whopping 80%. More and more retail investors have poured their money into the stock market to join the frenzy. But retail investors often lack the professional tools and knowledge to properly research a public company and value its stock.

As a result, many of them would turn to media such as newspaper, TV, social media platforms in attempt to get a sense of which direction the market is going. Nevertheless, stock prices sometimes react quickly to certain news, E.g. The market could dip as soon as the Fed’s chairman Powell announces its plan to slow down quantitative easing on national TV. Another example would be that the market usually goes up if positive news regarding the pandemic or the vaccine has come out the night before. This makes us wonder if the news can be valuable in the prediction of stock price.

(b) Problem Statement¶

To be more specific, we would like to know if the text of news headlines can predict the direction of the market or a company? To answer such question, we plan to apply the method of Naïve Bayes to a real-world dataset with historic records of stock price variation and news text. Upon such dataset, we would be able to build Naïve Bayes classifiers and try to predict the price movement.

(c) Data Description¶

Kaggler Aaron7sun prepared a great dataset which includes the top 25 headlines from Reddit World News Channel and Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) data from 2008/08/08 to 2016/07/01. There are 25 features that contain the top25 headlines text respectively. As for the only target, the label of 1 means the DJIA Adj Close value rose or stayed as the same; the label of 0 indicates the DJIA Adj Close value decreased.

01.Econometric Approach & Analytic Methods¶

(a) Naïve Bayes Algorithm¶

In this project, we used the Naïve Bayes Algorithm to classify the binary direction of the stock price. In our case, the stock price directions consist of Rise (Label=1) or No Rise (Label=0). The econometric theorem behind has three key components: Prior Probability, Likelihood and Marginal Likelihood. To illustrate the definition for each component, here we introduce a toy example.

Assuming there are 100 observations in our sample, and we only focus on two keywords “United” and “Attack”.

Then, the likelihood of the two labels can be calculated for each keyword:

Finally, the marginal likelihood of the two keywords can be calculated as the formulas below.

Appling Bayes' Theorem, we can obtain the probability of Rise and No Rise given the observed keywords.

Since 80% is larger than 20%, we would associate “United” with rising stock price with a probability of 80%.

As 60% is larger than 40%, we would associate “Attack” with rising stock price with a probability of 60%. One thing worth pointing out here is that the estimated probability could be highly biased if the assumption of independent features does not hold true, but that will not be a big problem for us since we focus more on the ranking of probabilities and the binary predictions.

(b) Techniques for Text Analysis¶

In data preprocessing and model refinement, several different techniques will be applied to text data analysis, including text cleaning, word cloud, stop words selection, sub-words splitting and so forth. However, such techniques are not the key for this project and will not be discussed in detail.

In [14]:



    


# text preprocess: remove stop words and words with 2 or less characters
def text_preprocess(text):
    result = []
    for token in gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(text) : # for every word in the text, convert them into a list of lowercase tokens and also ignoring tokens that are too short or too long
        if token not in gensim.parsing.preprocessing.STOPWORDS and len(token) > 2 and token not in stop_words:
            result.append(token)
            
    return ' '.join(result)

(c) Predictive Modelling: The Refined Model¶
Since the performace of the baseline model is not good, here we try to further engineer our features and try to improve its performance. The method we use is sub-words splitting.The algorithm below helps to divide words into sub-words with 2 or 3 characteristics automatically.













In [30]:



    


# taken from https://arxiv.org/abs/1508.07909
import pickle as pkl

def split_into_subwords(text):
    merges = pkl.load(open('E:/UCLA Econ Course/412 Fundamentals of Big Data/HW01/merge_ordered.pkl', 'rb')) # an encapsulated model
    subwords = []
    for word in text.split():
        for subword in merges:
            subword_count = word.count(subword)
            if subword_count > 0:
                word = word.replace(subword, ' ')
                subwords.extend([subword]*subword_count)
    return ' '.join(subwords)

03.Robustness Test¶
To futher test the robustness of our models, we will implement cross-validation for each model and plot their learning curves. In this part, we increase the size of training set step by step and plot the training accuracy and respective 10-fold cross-validation accuracy for each model.













In [39]:



    


from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
from sklearn.model_selection import ShuffleSplit

# learning curve
def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None,
                        n_jobs=1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    plt.figure()
    plt.title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
    # x
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    # y
    plt.ylabel("Score")
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    plt.grid()
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g",
             label="Cross-validation score")

    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    return plt



    













In [40]:



    


# learning curve for the baseline model
title = "Learning Curves (Naive Bayes)"
cv = ShuffleSplit(n_splits=10, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)
estimator = MultinomialNB()

We can see for the baseline model, the training score and cv score are very consistant over different sample size. The training score is close to 1 but the test performance is very similar to a random guess. A significant display of over-fitting.


For the refined model, we can tell the training score and cv score changes as the sample size goes up. Also, such two metrics become more stable as the sample size is over 2500. There still exist the problem of over-fitting, but we can conclude that sub-words splitting is an effective way to improve our prediction and justify the value of news headlines in the prediction of stock price.















04.Economic Insights¶
There are tons of factors play a role in the companies' stock proce, we justified the predictive value of news text in this project. We showed that news headlines contains valuable signals that can be captured by our naive bayes models to predict the direction of stock price.


By ploting the dominant words for each class, we can tell the high-frequency words are different between these two classes. For Rise cases, the most popular words are united, pilgrim, hitches and draw-round. For No Rise cases, those words change to german, hindrance, and operations. However, we can not directly make use of such difference by simply applying the Naive Bayes algorithm. The testing performace was not better than a random guess.


On the basis of some techniques of NLP, we successfully refined our baseline model and found that the testing accuracy of our new model was constantly higher than 50% given a relatively larger dataset. This result is inspiring to any applictions which are trying to include text data for a deeper understanding of stock price.















05.Summary and Future Improvement¶
In this project, we developed a whole pipeline to build an ML application of Naive Bayes, which display effectiveness in the prediction of stock price. Through EDA, NAs management and a series of processes of feature enginerring, we prepared our news text data and built two Naive Bayes classifiers. We also justified the robustness of our model by cross-validation.


Based on this application, we hope more trials and explorations will happen in this field for basic research on stocks or even more sophisticated predictive systems for solid investment suggestions. We believe there are at least two aspects where improvement is promising in the future works.


First, mitigating the problem of over-fitting. It is hard to provide satisfying prediction based on news data itself, datasets that contain richer information should be involved for a better prediction. Second, analyzing the market sentiment. Although the data could be limited, more advanced techniques make it posible to unleash valuable signals from the data. Sentiment analysis provides powerful techniques for us to obtain insights from text data. New sentiment predictors would be able to construct and potentially add value to our prediction.
